style='font-size:12.0pt'>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-.5in;text-align:justify'>&lt;span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>            Since bread was a food staple in ancient
near eastern societies, “bread” came to stand for food in general. As a result,
in the Bible “eat bread” usually means to eat or to eat a meal. New Testament
examples include Matthew&lt;b> 15&lt;/b>:2; Mark&lt;i> &lt;/i>&lt;b>3&lt;/b>:20; &lt;b>7&lt;/b>:2, 5;
Luke &lt;b>7&lt;/b>:33; &lt;b>14&lt;/b>:1, 15; John &lt;b>6&lt;/b>:31; &lt;b>13&lt;/b>:18 (&amp;lt; Psalm &lt;b>41&lt;/b>:9);
2 Thessalonians &lt;b>3&lt;/b>:8, 12. By further extension, in 1 Corinthians &lt;b>11&lt;/b>:26,
27, 28, 29 “eat bread” appears alongside “drink the cup” in Paul’s description
of observing the Lord’s Supper.&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>CANDIDATE FOR COMMUNION</title><link>https://christir.org/essays/topics/christian-doctrine/communion/candidate-for-communion/</link><pubDate>Thu, 02 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/essays/topics/christian-doctrine/communion/candidate-for-communion/</guid><description>&lt;style>
